  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "ES",
    "text": "I met Nathan and his two sons in 1983, when there was a celebration of the Brooklyn Bridge. His oldest son was filming at the Brooklyn Bridge Ceremony. And Nathan impressed me with his discussion of the design of the Brooklyn Bridge, and the metals that he designed on the Brooklyn Bridge. And I thought of him as a friend. And we went out for a few times. And then we couldn't be parted. We just felt like it was meant to be. It was bashert. And his life and mine intermeshed with the Holocaust now because we belong to many organizations that are involved in educating people on the Holocaust, and our friends are survivors. And so his life, his past life, has become part of mine, as well as the present. And I'm very happy to be his wife. And he's a wonderful person. And he's full of life. He's full of love and life. And to me, it's amazing that he went through such horrors and still be-- and he's still such a loving person, such a tender loving person. And his sons take after him. So I'm very happy about that.",
